# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gentoo-linux
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] In computing, a **compiler** is software that translates computer code written in one programming language (the *source* language) into another language (the *target* language).
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The name "compiler" is primarily used for programs that translate source code from a high-level programming language to a low-level programming language (e.g., assembly language, object code, or machine code) to create an executable program.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] There are many different types of compilers which produce output in different useful forms.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] A *cross-compiler* produces code for a different central processing unit (CPU) or operating system than the one on which the cross-compiler itself runs.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] A *bootstrap compiler* is often a temporary compiler, used for compiling a more permanent or better optimized compiler for a language.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Compilers generally implement these phases as modular components, promoting efficient design and correctness of transformations of source input to target output.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Program faults caused by incorrect compiler behavior can be very difficult to track down and work around; therefore, compiler implementers invest significant effort to ensure compiler correctness.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] With respect to making source code runnable, an interpreter provides a similar function as a compiler, but via a different mechanism.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] An interpreter executes code without converting it to machine code.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Therefore, some interpreters execute source code while others execute an intermediate form such as bytecode.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] A program compiled to native code tends to run faster than when interpreted, while environments with a bytecode-intermediate-form tends toward intermediate-speed.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Alternatively, just-in-time compilation allows for native execution speed with a one-time startup processing time cost.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Low-level programming languages, such as assembly and C, are typically compiled, especially when speed is a significant concern, rather than having cross-platform support.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] For such languages, there are more one-to-one correspondences between the source code and the resulting machine code, making it easier for programmers to control the use of hardware.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] In theory, any programming language can be used via either a compiler or an interpreter, but in practice, languages tend to be used with only one or the other.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Nonetheless, it is possible to write a compiler for a language that is commonly interpreted.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] For example, Common Lisp can be compiled to Java bytecode (and then interpreted by the Java virtual machine), to C code (which can then be compiled again to native machine code), or directly to native code.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Theoretical computing concepts developed by scientists, mathematicians, and engineers formed the basis of digital modern computing development during World War II.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Primitive binary languages evolved because digital devices only understand ones and zeros and the circuit patterns in the underlying machine architecture.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] In the late 1940s, assembly languages were created to offer a more workable abstraction of the computer architectures.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Limited memory capacity of early computers led to substantial technical challenges when the first compilers were designed.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Therefore, the compiling process needed to be divided into several small programs.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The front end programs produce the analysis products used by the back end programs to generate target code.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] As computer technology provided more resources, compiler designs could align better with the compiling process.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] It is usually more productive for a programmer to use a high-level language, so the development of high-level languages followed naturally from the abilities offered by digital computers.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] High-level languages are formal languages that are strictly defined by their syntax and semantics which form the high-level language architecture.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The sentences in a language may be defined by a set of rules called a grammar.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Backus–Naur form (BNF) describes the syntax of "sentences" of a language.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] It was developed by John Backus and used for the syntax of Algol 60.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The ideas derive from the context-free grammar concepts by linguist Noam Chomsky.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] "BNF and its extensions have become standard tools for describing the syntax of programming notations.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Between 1942 and 1945, Konrad Zuse designed the first (algorithmic) programming language for computers named *Plankalkül* ("Plan Calculus").
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Zuse also envisioned a *Planfertigungsgerät* ("Plan assembly device") to automatically translate the mathematical formulation of a program into machine-readable punched film stock.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] While no implementation occurred until the 1970s, it presented concepts later seen in APL designed by Ken Iverson in the late 1950s.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] APL is a language for mathematical computations.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Between 1949 and 1951, Heinz Rutishauser proposed Superplan, a high-level language and automatic translator.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] His ideas were later refined by Friedrich L.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Compiler technology evolved from the need for a strictly defined transformation of the high-level source program into a low-level target program for the digital computer.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The compiler could be viewed as a front end to deal with the analysis of the source code and a back end to synthesize the analysis into the target code.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Optimization between the front end and back end could produce more efficient target code.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Early operating systems and software were written in assembly language.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] In the 1960s and early 1970s, the use of high-level languages for system programming was still controversial due to resource limitations.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] However, several research and industry efforts began the shift toward high-level systems programming languages, for example, BCPL, BLISS, B, and C.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] BCPL (Basic Combined Programming Language) designed in 1966 by Martin Richards at the University of Cambridge was originally developed as a compiler writing tool.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Several compilers have been implemented, Richards' book provides insights to the language and its compiler.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] BCPL was not only an influential systems programming language that is still used in research but also provided a basis for the design of B and C languages.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] BLISS (Basic Language for Implementation of System Software) was developed for a Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-10 computer by W.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Wulf's Carnegie Mellon University (CMU) research team.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The CMU team went on to develop BLISS-11 compiler one year later in 1970.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Multics (Multiplexed Information and Computing Service), a time-sharing operating system project, involved MIT, Bell Labs, General Electric (later Honeywell) and was led by Fernando Corbató from MIT.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Multics was written in the PL/I language developed by IBM and IBM User Group.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] IBM's goal was to satisfy business, scientific, and systems programming requirements.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] There were other languages that could have been considered but PL/I offered the most complete solution even though it had not been implemented.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] For the first few years of the Multics project, a subset of the language could be compiled to assembly language with the Early PL/I (EPL) compiler by Doug McIlory and Bob Morris from Bell Labs.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] EPL supported the project until a boot-strapping compiler for the full PL/I could be developed.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Bell Labs left the Multics project in 1969, and developed a system programming language B based on BCPL concepts, written by Dennis Ritchie and Ken Thompson.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Ritchie created a boot-strapping compiler for B and wrote Unics (Uniplexed Information and Computing Service) operating system for a PDP-7 in B.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Bell Labs started the development and expansion of C based on B and BCPL.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The BCPL compiler had been transported to Multics by Bell Labs and BCPL was a preferred language at Bell Labs.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Initially, a front-end program to Bell Labs' B compiler was used while a C compiler was developed.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] In 1971, a new PDP-11 provided the resource to define extensions to B and rewrite the compiler.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] By 1973 the design of C language was essentially complete and the Unix kernel for a PDP-11 was rewritten in C.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Steve Johnson started development of Portable C Compiler (PCC) to support retargeting of C compilers to new machines.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Object-oriented programming (OOP) offered some interesting possibilities for application development and maintenance.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] OOP concepts go further back but were part of LISP and Simula language science.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Bell Labs became interested in OOP with the development of C++.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] C++ was first used in 1980 for systems programming.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The initial design leveraged C language systems programming abilities with Simula concepts.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Object-oriented facilities were added in 1983.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The Cfront program implemented a C++ front-end for C84 language compiler.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] In subsequent years several C++ compilers were developed as C++ popularity grew.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] In many application domains, the idea of using a higher-level language quickly caught on.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Because of the expanding functionality supported by newer programming languages and the increasing complexity of computer architectures, compilers became more complex.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] DARPA (Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency) sponsored a compiler project with Wulf's CMU research team in 1970.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The Production Quality Compiler-Compiler PQCC design would produce a Production Quality Compiler (PQC) from formal definitions of source language and the target.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] PQCC tried to extend the term compiler-compiler beyond the traditional meaning as a parser generator (e.g., Yacc) without much success.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] PQCC might more properly be referred to as a compiler generator.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] PQCC research into code generation process sought to build a truly automatic compiler-writing system.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The effort discovered and designed the phase structure of the PQC.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The BLISS-11 compiler provided the initial structure.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The phases included analyses (front end), intermediate translation to virtual machine (middle end), and translation to the target (back end).
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] TCOL was developed for the PQCC research to handle language specific constructs in the intermediate representation.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Variations of TCOL supported various languages.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The PQCC project investigated techniques of automated compiler construction.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The design concepts proved useful in optimizing compilers and compilers for the (since 1995, object-oriented) programming language Ada.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The Ada *STONEMAN* document formalized the program support environment (APSE) along with the kernel (KAPSE) and minimal (MAPSE).
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] An Ada interpreter NYU/ED supported development and standardization efforts with the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) and the International Standards Organization (ISO).
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Initial Ada compiler development by the U.S.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Military Services included the compilers in a complete integrated design environment along the lines of the *STONEMAN* document.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Army and Navy worked on the Ada Language System (ALS) project targeted to DEC/VAX architecture while the Air Force started on the Ada Integrated Environment (AIE) targeted to IBM 370 series.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] While the projects did not provide the desired results, they did contribute to the overall effort on Ada development.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Other Ada compiler efforts got underway in Britain at the University of York and in Germany at the University of Karlsruhe.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] S., Verdix (later acquired by Rational) delivered the Verdix Ada Development System (VADS) to the Army.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] VADS provided a set of development tools including a compiler.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Unix/VADS could be hosted on a variety of Unix platforms such as DEC Ultrix and the Sun 3/60 Solaris targeted to Motorola 68020 in an Army CECOM evaluation.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] There were soon many Ada compilers available that passed the Ada Validation tests.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The Free Software Foundation GNU project developed the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) which provides a core capability to support multiple languages and targets.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The Ada version GNAT is one of the most widely used Ada compilers.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] GNAT is free but there is also commercial support, for example, AdaCore, was founded in 1994 to provide commercial software solutions for Ada.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] GNAT Pro includes the GNU GCC based GNAT with a tool suite to provide an integrated development environment.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] High-level languages continued to drive compiler research and development.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Focus areas included optimization and automatic code generation.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Trends in programming languages and development environments influenced compiler technology.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] More compilers became included in language distributions (PERL, Java Development Kit) and as a component of an IDE (VADS, Eclipse, Ada Pro).
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The interrelationship and interdependence of technologies grew.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The advent of web services promoted growth of web languages and scripting languages.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Scripts trace back to the early days of Command Line Interfaces (CLI) where the user could enter commands to be executed by the system.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] User Shell concepts developed with languages to write shell programs.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Early Windows designs offered a simple batch programming capability.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The conventional transformation of these language used an interpreter.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] While not widely used, Bash and Batch compilers have been written.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] More recently sophisticated interpreted languages became part of the developers tool kit.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Modern scripting languages include PHP, Python, Ruby and Lua.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] (Lua is widely used in game development.) All of these have interpreter and compiler support.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] "When the field of compiling began in the late 50s, its focus was limited to the translation of high-level language programs into machine code ...
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The compiler field is increasingly intertwined with other disciplines including computer architecture, programming languages, formal methods, software engineering, and computer security." The "Compiler Research: The Next 50 Years" article noted the importance of object-oriented languages and Java.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Security and parallel computing were cited among the future research targets.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] A compiler implements a formal transformation from a high-level source program to a low-level target program.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Compiler design can define an end-to-end solution or tackle a defined subset that interfaces with other compiling tools e.g., preprocessors, assemblers, linkers.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Design requirements include rigorously defined interfaces both internally between compiler components and externally between supporting toolsets.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] In the early days, the approach taken to compiler design was directly affected by the complexity of the computer language to be processed, the experience of the person(s) designing it, and the resources available.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Resource limitations led to the need to pass through the source code more than once.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] A compiler for a relatively simple language written by one person might be a single, monolithic piece of software.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] However, as the source language grows in complexity the design may be split into a number of interdependent phases.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Separate phases provide design improvements that focus development on the functions in the compiling process.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Classifying compilers by number of passes has its background in the hardware resource limitations of computers.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Compiling involves performing much work and early computers did not have enough memory to contain one program that did all of this work.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] As a result, compilers were split up into smaller programs which each made a pass over the source (or some representation of it) performing some of the required analysis and translations.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The ability to compile in a single pass has classically been seen as a benefit because it simplifies the job of writing a compiler and one-pass compilers generally compile source code faster than multi-pass compilers.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Thus, partly driven by the resource limits of early systems, many early languages were specifically designed so that they could be compiled in one pass (e.g., Pascal).
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] In some cases, the design of a language feature may require a compiler to perform more than one pass over the source.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] For example, consider a declaration appearing on line 20 of the source which affects the translation of a statement appearing on line 10.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] In this case, the first pass needs to gather information about declarations appearing after statements that they affect, with the translation then performed during a subsequent pass.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The disadvantage of compiling in a single pass is that it is not possible to perform many of the sophisticated optimizations needed to generate high quality code.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] It can be difficult to count exactly how many passes an optimizing compiler makes.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] For instance, different phases of optimization may analyse one expression many times but only analyse another expression once.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Splitting a compiler up into small programs is a technique used by researchers interested in producing provably correct compilers.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Proving the correctness of a set of small programs often requires less effort than proving the correctness of a larger, single, equivalent program.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Regardless of the exact number of phases in the compiler design, the phases can be assigned to one of three stages.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The stages include a front end, a middle end, and a back end.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] This front/middle/back-end approach makes it possible to combine front ends for different languages with back ends for different CPUs while sharing the optimizations of the middle end.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Practical examples of this approach are the GNU Compiler Collection, Clang (LLVM-based C/C++ compiler), and the Amsterdam Compiler Kit, which have multiple front-ends, shared optimizations and multiple back-ends.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The front end analyzes the source code to build an internal representation of the program, called the intermediate representation (IR).
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] It also manages the symbol table, a data structure mapping each symbol in the source code to associated information such as location, type and scope.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] While the frontend can be a single monolithic function or program, as in a scannerless parser, it was traditionally implemented and analyzed as several phases, which may execute sequentially or concurrently.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] This method is favored due to its modularity and separation of concerns.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Most commonly, the frontend is broken into three phases: lexical analysis (also known as lexing or scanning), syntax analysis (also known as scanning or parsing), and semantic analysis.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Lexing and parsing comprise the syntactic analysis (word syntax and phrase syntax, respectively), and in simple cases, these modules (the lexer and parser) can be automatically generated from a grammar for the language, though in more complex cases these require manual modification.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The lexical grammar and phrase grammar are usually context-free grammars, which simplifies analysis significantly, with context-sensitivity handled at the semantic analysis phase.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The semantic analysis phase is generally more complex and written by hand, but can be partially or fully automated using attribute grammars.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] These phases themselves can be further broken down: lexing as scanning and evaluating, and parsing as building a concrete syntax tree (CST, parse tree) and then transforming it into an abstract syntax tree (AST, syntax tree).
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] In some cases additional phases are used, notably *line reconstruction* and *preprocessing,* but these are rare.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The middle end, also known as *optimizer,* performs optimizations on the intermediate representation in order to improve the performance and the quality of the produced machine code.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The middle end contains those optimizations that are independent of the CPU architecture being targeted.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Compiler analysis is the prerequisite for any compiler optimization, and they tightly work together.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] For example, dependence analysis is crucial for loop transformation.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The scope of compiler analysis and optimizations vary greatly; their scope may range from operating within a basic block, to whole procedures, or even the whole program.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] There is a trade-off between the granularity of the optimizations and the cost of compilation.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] For example, peephole optimizations are fast to perform during compilation but only affect a small local fragment of the code, and can be performed independently of the context in which the code fragment appears.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] In contrast, interprocedural optimization requires more compilation time and memory space, but enable optimizations that are only possible by considering the behavior of multiple functions simultaneously.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Interprocedural analysis and optimizations are common in modern commercial compilers from HP, IBM, SGI, Intel, Microsoft, and Sun Microsystems.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The free software GCC was criticized for a long time for lacking powerful interprocedural optimizations, but it is changing in this respect.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Another open source compiler with full analysis and optimization infrastructure is Open64, which is used by many organizations for research and commercial purposes.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Due to the extra time and space needed for compiler analysis and optimizations, some compilers skip them by default.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Users have to use compilation options to explicitly tell the compiler which optimizations should be enabled.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The back end is responsible for the CPU architecture specific optimizations and for code generation.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Compiler correctness is the branch of software engineering that deals with trying to show that a compiler behaves according to its language specification.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Techniques include developing the compiler using formal methods and using rigorous testing (often called compiler validation) on an existing compiler.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Higher-level programming languages usually appear with a type of translation in mind: either designed as compiled language or interpreted language.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] However, in practice there is rarely anything about a language that *requires* it to be exclusively compiled or exclusively interpreted, although it is possible to design languages that rely on re-interpretation at run time.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The categorization usually reflects the most popular or widespread implementations of a language.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] For instance, BASIC is sometimes called an interpreted language, and C a compiled one, despite the existence of BASIC compilers and C interpreters.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Interpretation does not replace compilation completely.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] It only hides it from the user and makes it gradual.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Even though an interpreter can itself be interpreted, a set of directly executed machine instructions is needed somewhere at the bottom of the execution stack (see machine language).
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Furthermore, for optimization compilers can contain interpreter functionality, and interpreters may include ahead of time compilation techniques.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] For example, where an expression can be executed during compilation and the results inserted into the output program, then it prevents it having to be recalculated each time the program runs, which can greatly speed up the final program.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Modern trends toward just-in-time compilation and bytecode interpretation at times blur the traditional categorizations of compilers and interpreters even further.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Meta-tracing is an automated compiler synthesis approach which takes this further and can be used to synthesize a compiler from a language interpreter.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Some language specifications spell out that implementations *must* include a compilation facility; for example, Common Lisp.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] However, there is nothing inherent in the definition of Common Lisp that stops it from being interpreted.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] To implement these features in a compiled language, programs must usually be shipped with a runtime library that includes a version of the compiler itself.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] One classification of compilers is by the platform on which their generated code executes.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] A *native* or *hosted* compiler is one whose output is intended to directly run on the same type of computer and operating system that the compiler itself runs on.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The output of a cross compiler is designed to run on a different platform.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Cross compilers are often used when developing software for embedded systems that are not intended to support a software development environment.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The output of a compiler that produces code for a virtual machine (VM) may or may not be executed on the same platform as the compiler that produced it.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] For this reason, such compilers are not usually classified as native or cross compilers.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The lower level language that is the target of a compiler may itself be a high-level programming language.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] C, viewed by some as a sort of portable assembly language, is frequently the target language of such compilers.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] For example, Cfront, the original compiler for C++, used C as its target language.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] The C code generated by such a compiler is usually not intended to be readable and maintained by humans, so indent style and creating pretty C intermediate code are ignored.
[src:gentoo-linux/compiler] Some of the features of C that make it a good target language include the `#line` directive, which can be generated by the compiler to support debugging of the original source, and the wide platform support available with C compilers.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Gentoo package management is designed to be modular, portable, easy to maintain, and flexible.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Gentoo describes itself as a meta-distribution because of its adaptability, in that the majority of its users have configurations and sets of installed programs which are unique to the system and the applications they use.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Gentoo Linux is named after the gentoo penguin, the fastest swimming species of penguin.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The name was chosen to reflect the potential speed improvements of machine-specific optimizing, which is a major feature of Gentoo.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Gentoo Linux was initially created by Daniel Robbins as the *Enoch Linux* distribution.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Its design philosophy was that of precompiled binaries which were tuned to the hardware and that only included required programs.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] At least one version of Enoch was distributed under that name: version 0.75, in December 1999.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] An older release labeled "Enoch 0.5" can be found on the CD accompanying the August 1999 edition of the Danish computer magazine *Alt om Data*.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Daniel Robbins and the other contributors experimented with a fork of GCC known as EGCS, developed by Cygnus Solutions.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] It was at this point that "Enoch" was renamed "Gentoo" Linux.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The modifications to EGCS eventually became part of the official GCC (version 2.95); Gentoo and other Linux distros benefited from similar speed increases.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Gentoo Linux 1.0 was released on March 31, 2002.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] In 2004, Robbins set up the non-profit Gentoo Foundation, transferred all copyrights and trademarks to it, and stepped down as chief architect of the project.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The current board of trustees is composed of five members who were announced (following an election) on March 2, 2008.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The seven-member Gentoo Council oversees related technical issues and policies.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The Gentoo Council members are elected annually, for a period of one year, by the active Gentoo developers.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] When a member of the Council retires, the successor is voted into place by the existing Council members.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The Gentoo Foundation is a domestic non-profit corporation, registered in the State of New Mexico.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] In late 2007, the Foundation's charter was revoked, but by May 2008 the State of New Mexico declared that the Gentoo Foundation, Inc. had returned to good standing and was free to do business.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The creator of Gentoo, Daniel Robbins, left the project in both 2004 and 2007 due to conflicts with other developers.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Gentoo is aimed at Linux users who prefer a high degree of control over the software installed and running on their computer.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Users who invest time in configuring and optimizing a Gentoo system can build efficient desktops and servers.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Gentoo supports building a Linux kernel tailored to specific hardware.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] It provides detailed control over which services are installed and running, including the option to choose between systemd or OpenRC as the default init system, among other possibilities.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Memory usage may also be reduced compared to some other distributions by omitting unnecessary kernel features and services.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Gentoo's package repositories provide a large collection of software.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Each package contains details of any dependencies, so only the minimum set of packages need to be installed.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Optional features of individual packages, such as whether they require LDAP or Qt support, can be selected by the user and any resulting package requirements are automatically included in the set of dependencies.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Gentoo itself does not have a default look and feel, hence installed packages usually appear as their authors intended.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Portage is Gentoo's software distribution and package management system.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The original design was based on the ports system used by the Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD) operating systems.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The Gentoo repository contains over 19,000 packages.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] A single invocation of portage's emerge command can update the local copy of the Gentoo repository, search for a package, or download, compile, and install one or more packages and their dependencies.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The built-in features can be set for individual packages, or globally, with so-called "USE flags".
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Pre-compiled binaries are provided for some applications with long build times, such as LibreOffice and Mozilla Firefox, but users lose the ability to customize optional features.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] There are configuration options to reduce compiling times, such as by enabling parallel compiling or using pipes instead of temporary files.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Package compiling may also be distributed over multiple computers.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Additionally, the user may be able to mount a large filesystem in memory to further speed up the process of building packages.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Some approaches have drawbacks and are not enabled by default.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] When installing the same package on multiple computers with sufficiently similar hardware, the package may be compiled once and a binary package created for quick installation on the other computers.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] On December 29, 2023, it was announced that Gentoo will offer binary packages for download and direct installation.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] For most architectures, this will be limited to the core system and weekly updates.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] For amd64 and arm64 however the availability of binary packages reaches over 20 GB.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] As Gentoo is a source-based distribution with a repository describing how to build the packages, adding instructions to build on different machine architectures is particularly easy.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Originally built on the IA-32 architecture, Gentoo has since been ported to many others.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] It is officially supported and considered stable on IA-32, x86-64, PA-RISC, 32-bit and 64-bit PowerPC, 64-bit SPARC, DEC Alpha, and 32- and 64-bit ARM architectures.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] It is also officially supported but considered in-development state on MIPS, PS3 Cell Processor, System Z/s390.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Official support for 32-bit SPARC, SuperH and Itanium have been dropped.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Portability towards other operating systems, such as those derived from Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD), including macOS, is under active development by the Gentoo/Alt project.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The Gentoo/FreeBSD project already has a working guide based on FreeSBIE, while Gentoo/NetBSD, Gentoo/OpenBSD and Gentoo/DragonFly are being developed.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] A project exists to get Portage working on OpenSolaris.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] An experimental port to GNU Hurd was released on April 1, 2026.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] It is also possible to install a Gentoo Prefix (provided by a project that maintains alternative installation methods for Gentoo) in a Cygwin environment on Windows, but this configuration is experimental.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Gentoo may be installed in several ways.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The most common is to use the Gentoo minimal CD with a stage3 tarball (explained below).
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] As with many Linux distributions, Gentoo may be installed from almost any Linux environment, such as another Linux distribution's Live CD, Live USB, or Network Booting using the "Gentoo Alternative Install Guide".
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] A normal install requires a connection to the Internet, but a network-less install guide exists.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] On April 3, 2022, it was announced that there would be a new official image with a GUI, called the LiveGUI image.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] This can be installed onto installation media such as a USB drive or a dual-layer DVD.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] It includes a large selection of software, including the KDE Plasma 6 desktop environment, image editors, office software, system administration, and installation tools.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Previously, Gentoo supported installation from stage1 and stage2 tarballs.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The Gentoo Foundation no longer recommends this usage; stage1 and stage2 are now meant only for Gentoo developers.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Following the initial install steps, the Gentoo Linux install process in the Gentoo Handbook describes compiling a new Linux kernel.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] This process is generally not required by other Linux distributions.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Although the installation requires significantly more configuration than most mainline distributions, Gentoo provides documentation and tools such as its stage3 tarball and distribution kernels to simplify the process.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] In addition, users may also use an existing kernel known to work on their system by simply copying it to the boot directory, or installing one of the provided pre-compiled kernel packages, and updating their bootloader.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Support for installation is provided on the Gentoo forum, Reddit, and IRC.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] A Live USB of Gentoo Linux can be created manually, by using various tools, or with dd as described in the handbook.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Since October 2005, only the stage3 installations have been officially supported, due to the inherent complexities of bootstrapping from earlier stages (which requires resolving and then breaking numerous circular dependencies).
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Tarballs for stage1 and stage2 were distributed for some time after this, although the instructions for installing from these stages had been removed from the handbook and moved into the Gentoo FAQ.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] As of September 2015, only the supported stage3 tarballs are publicly available; stage1 and stage2 tarballs are only "officially" generated and used internally by Gentoo development teams.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] However, if so desired, a user may still rebuild the toolchain or reinstall the base system software during or after a normal stage3 installation, effectively simulating the old bootstrap process.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] From 2003 until 2008, the **Gentoo Reference Platform** (GRP) was a snapshot of prebuilt packages that users could quickly install during the Gentoo installation process, to give faster access to a fully functional Gentoo installation.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] These packages included KDE, X Window System, OpenOffice, GNOME, and Mozilla.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Once the installation was complete, the packages installed as part of the GRP were intended to be replaced by the user with the same or newer versions built through Portage that would be built using the user's system configuration rather than the generic builds provided by the GRP.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] As of 2011, the GRP is discontinued, the final reference to it appearing in the 2008.0 handbook.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Like other Linux distributions, Gentoo systems have an `/etc/gentoo-release` file, but this contains the version of the installed `sys-apps/baselayout` package.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] In 2004, Gentoo began to version its Live media by year rather than numerically.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] This continued until 2008, when it was announced that the 2008.1 Live CD release had been cancelled in favour of weekly automated builds of both Stages 3 and Minimal CDs.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] On December 20, 2008, the first weekly builds were published.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] In 2009, a special Live DVD was created to celebrate the Gentoo 10-year anniversary.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] In 2009, a special Live DVD was released to celebrate Gentoo's tenth anniversary.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Initially planned as a one-off, the Live DVD was updated to the latest package versions in 2011 due to its popularity among new users.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Although Gentoo does not have a concept of versioning the entire system, it does make use of "profiles", which define build configuration for all packages in the system.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Major changes, such as changing the layout of how files are installed across the entire system, typically involve a profile upgrade and may require rebuilding all installed software.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] These profiles are versioned based on the year they were released, and include several variants for each release targeted towards different types of systems (such as servers and desktops).
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Profiles formerly tracked the versioning of install media, and switched to two-digit year naming after the discontinuation of versioned media.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Hardened Gentoo is a project designed to develop and designate a set of add-ons that are useful when a more security focused installation is required.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Previously, the project included patches to produce a hardened kernel, but these were discontinued.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Other parts of the hardened set, such as SELinux, and userspace hardening remain.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] In June 2018 the Gentoo GitHub code repository mirror used mainly by developers was hacked after an attacker gained access to an organization administrator's account via deducing the password.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Gentoo promptly responded by containing the attack and improving security practices.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] No Gentoo cryptography keys or signed packages were compromised, and the repository was restored after five days.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The gentoo penguin is thought to be the fastest underwater-swimming penguin.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] The name Gentoo Linux is a reference both to the omnibus Linux mascot— a penguin called Tux— and the project's aim to produce a high-performance operating system.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Unofficial mascots include *Larry The Cow* and *Znurt the Flying Saucer*.
[src:gentoo-linux/gentoo-linux] Several independently developed Gentoo Linux variants exist, as do products built off of Gentoo such as ChromiumOS.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] A **Linux distribution**, often abbreviated as **distro**, is an operating system that includes the Linux kernel for its kernel functionality.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Although the name does not imply product distribution per se, a distro—if distributed on its own—is often obtained via a website intended specifically for the purpose.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Distros have been designed for a wide variety of systems ranging from personal computers (for example, Linux Mint and Zorin OS) to servers (for example, Red Hat Enterprise Linux) and from embedded devices (for example, OpenWrt) to supercomputers (for example, Rocks Cluster Distribution).
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] A distro typically includes many components in addition to the Linux kernel.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Commonly, it includes a package manager, an init system (such as systemd, OpenRC, SysVinit, or runit), GNU tools and libraries, documentation, IP network configuration utilities, the getty TTY setup program, and many more.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Typically, most of the included software is free and open-source software – made available both as binary for convenience and as source code to allow for modifying it.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] A distro may also include proprietary software that is not available in source code form, such as a device driver binary.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] A distro may be described as a particular assortment of application and utility software (various GNU tools and libraries, for example), packaged with the Linux kernel in such a way that its capabilities meet users' needs.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The software is usually adapted to the distribution and then combined into software packages by the distribution's maintainers.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The software packages are available online in repositories, which are storage locations usually distributed around the world.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Beside "glue" components, such as the distribution installers (for example, Debian-Installer and Anaconda) and the package management systems, very few packages are actually written by a distribution's maintainers.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Distributions have been designed for a wide range of computing environments, including desktops, servers, laptops, netbooks, mobile devices (phones and tablets), and embedded systems.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] There are commercially backed distributions, such as Red Hat Enterprise Linux (Red Hat), openSUSE (SUSE) and Ubuntu (Canonical), and entirely community-driven distributions, such as Debian, Slackware, Gentoo and Arch Linux.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Most distributions come ready-to-use and prebuilt for a specific instruction set, while some (such as Gentoo) are distributed mostly in source code form and must be built before installation.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Linus Torvalds developed the Linux kernel and distributed its first version, 0.01, in 1991.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Linux was initially distributed as source code only, and later as a pair of downloadable floppy disk images: one bootable and containing the Linux kernel itself, and the other with a set of GNU utilities and tools for setting up a file system.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Since the installation procedure was complicated, especially in the face of growing amounts of available software, distributions sprang up to simplify it.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The two oldest, still active distribution projects started in 1993.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The SLS distribution was not well maintained, so in July 1993 a new SLS-based distribution, Slackware, was released by Patrick Volkerding.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Also dissatisfied with SLS, Ian Murdock set to create a free distribution by founding Debian in August 1993, with first public BETA released in January 1994 and first stable version in June 1996.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Users were attracted to Linux distributions as alternatives to MS-DOS compatible operating systems, Windows, Classic Mac OS, and proprietary versions of Unix.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Most early adopters were familiar with Unix from work or school.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] They embraced Linux distributions for their low (or absent) cost, and the availability of the source code for most or all of their software.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] As of 2025, Linux has become more popular in server and embedded devices markets than in the desktop market.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] It is used in approximately 64.5% of web servers; its current operating system market share is about 2.51%, and its desktop operating system market share is about 2.94%.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide an installation system akin to that provided with other modern operating systems.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Other distributions, including Gentoo Linux, provide only the binaries of a basic kernel, compilation tools, and an installer; the installer compiles all the requested software for the specific architecture of the user's computer, using these tools and the software's source code.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Distributions are normally segmented into *packages*.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Each package contains a specific application or service.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Examples of packages are a library for handling the PNG image format, a collection of fonts, and a web browser.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The package is typically provided as compiled code, with installation and removal of packages handled by a package management system (PMS) rather than a simple file archiver.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Each package intended for such a PMS contains meta-information such as its description, version number, and its dependencies (other packages it requires to run).
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The package management system evaluates this meta-information to allow package searches, perform automatic upgrades to newer versions, and to check that all dependencies of a package are present (and either notify the user to install them, or install them automatically).
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The package can also be provided as source code to be compiled on the system.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Most distributions install packages, including the kernel and other core operating system components, in a predetermined configuration.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] A few now require or permit configuration adjustments at first install time.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] This makes installation less daunting, particularly for new users, but is not always acceptable.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] For specific requirements, much software must be carefully configured to be useful, to work correctly with other software, or to be secure, and local administrators are often obliged to spend time reviewing and reconfiguring it.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Some (but not all) distributions go to considerable lengths to adjust and customize the software they include, and some provide configuration tools to help users do so.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] By obtaining and installing *everything* normally provided in a distribution, an administrator may create a "distribution less" installation.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] It is possible to build such systems from scratch, avoiding distributions altogether.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] One needs a way to generate the first binaries until the system is *self-hosting*.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] This can be done via compilation on another system capable of building binaries for the intended target (possibly by cross-compilation).
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions is due to technical, organizational, and philosophical variation among vendors and users.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The permissive licensing of free software means that users with sufficient knowledge and interest can customize any extant distribution, or design one to suit their own needs.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Rolling Linux distributions are kept current using small and frequent updates.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The terms *partially rolling* and *partly rolling* (along with synonyms *semi-rolling* and *half-rolling*), *fully rolling*, *truly rolling* and *optionally rolling* are sometimes used by software developers and users.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Repositories of **rolling distributions** usually contain very recent software releases—often the latest stable versions available.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] They have pseudo-releases and installation media that are simply snapshots of the distribution at the time of the installation image's release.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Typically, a rolling-release OS installed from older installation medium can be fully updated after it is installed.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Depending on the usage case, there can be pros and cons to both standard release and rolling release software development methodologies.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] In terms of the software development process, **standard releases** require significant development effort to keep old versions up-to-date by propagating bug fixes back to the newest branch, versus focusing on the newest development branch.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Also, unlike rolling releases, standard releases require more than one code branch to be developed and maintained, which increases the workload of the software developers and maintainers.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] On the other hand, software features and technology planning are easier in standard releases due to a better understanding of upcoming features in the next version(s).
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Software release cycles can also be synchronized with those of major upstream software projects, such as desktop environments.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] As for the user experience, standard releases are often viewed as more stable and bug-free since software conflicts can be more easily addressed and the software stack more thoroughly tested and evaluated, during the software development cycle.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] For this reason, they tend to be the preferred choice in enterprise environments and mission-critical tasks.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] However, rolling releases offer more current software which can also provide increased stability and fewer software bugs along with the additional benefits of new features, greater functionality, faster running speeds, and improved system and application security.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Regarding software security, the rolling release model can have advantages in timely security updates, fixing system or application security bugs and vulnerabilities, that standard releases may have to wait till the next release for or patch in various versions.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] In a rolling release distribution, where the user has chosen to run it as a highly dynamic system, the constant flux of software packages can introduce new unintended vulnerabilities.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] A "live" distribution is a Linux distribution that can be booted from removable storage media such as optical discs or USB flash drives, instead of being installed on and booted from a hard disk drive.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The portability of installation-free distributions makes them advantageous for applications such as demonstrations, borrowing someone else's computer, rescue operations, or as installation media for a standard distribution.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] When the operating system is booted from a read-only medium such as a CD or DVD, any user data that needs to be retained between sessions cannot be stored on the boot device but must be written to another storage device, such as a USB flash drive or a hard disk drive.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide a "live" form in addition to their conventional form, which is a network-based or removable-media image intended to be used only for installation; such distributions include antiX, SUSE, Ubuntu, Linux Mint, MX Linux and Fedora Linux.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Some distributions, including Knoppix, Puppy Linux, Devil-Linux, SuperGamer, SliTaz GNU/Linux and dyne:bolic, are designed primarily for live use.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Additionally, some minimal distributions can be run directly from as little space as one floppy disk without the need to change the contents of the system's hard disk drive.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The website DistroWatch lists many Linux distributions and displays some of the ones that have the most web traffic on the site.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The Wikimedia Foundation released an analysis of the browser User Agents of visitors to WMF websites until 2015, which includes details of the most popular Operating System identifiers, including some Linux distributions.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Many of the popular distributions are listed below.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Whether such operating systems count as a "Linux distribution" is a controversial topic.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] They use the Linux kernel, so the Linux Foundation and Chris DiBona, Google's former open-source chief, agree that Android is a Linux distribution; others, such as Google engineer Patrick Brady, disagree by noting the lack of support for many GNU tools in Android, including glibc.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Other Linux-kernel-based operating systems include Tizen, Mer/Sailfish OS, KaiOS and Amazon's Kindle firmware.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Lightweight Linux distributions are those that have been designed with support for older hardware in mind, allowing older hardware to still be used productively, or, for maximum possible speed in newer hardware by leaving more resources available for use by applications.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Examples include antiX, Damn Small Linux (based on antiX), Tiny Core Linux, Puppy Linux and Slitaz.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The Free Standards Group was an organization formed by major software and hardware vendors that aims to improve interoperability between different distributions.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Among their proposed standards are the Linux Standard Base, which defines a common ABI and packaging system for Linux, and the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard which recommends a standard file naming chart, notably the basic directory names found on the root of the tree of any Linux filesystem.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Those standards, however, see limited use, even among the distributions developed by members of the organization.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions means that not all software runs on all distributions, depending on what libraries and other system attributes are required.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Packaged software and software repositories are usually specific to a particular distribution, though cross-installation is sometimes possible on closely related distributions.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] One of solutions for interdistribution issues, particularly to run software created for a distribution on another, is by using container such as Distrobox.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] There are several ways to install a Linux distribution.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The most popular method of installing Linux is by booting from a live USB memory stick, which can be created by using a USB image writer application and the ISO image, which can be downloaded from various Linux distribution websites.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] DVD disks, CD disks, network installations and even other hard drives can also be used as "installation media".
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] In the 1990s, Linux distributions were installed using sets of floppy disks, but this has been abandoned by all major distributions.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] By the 2000s, many distributions offered CD and DVD sets with the vital packages on the first disk and less important packages on later ones.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Some distributions, such as Debian also enabled installing over a network after booting from either a set of floppy disks or a CD with only a small amount of data on it.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] New users tend to begin by partitioning a hard drive to keep their formerly installed operating system.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The Linux distribution can then be installed on its own separate partition without affecting formerly saved data.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] In a Live CD setup, the computer boots the entire operating system from CD without first installing it on the computer's hard disk.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Many distributions have a Live CD *installer*, where the computer boots the operating system from the disk, and it can then be installed on the computer's hard disk, providing a seamless transition from the OS running from the CD to the OS running from the hard disk.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Both servers and personal computers that come with Linux already installed are available from vendors including Hewlett-Packard, Dell and System76.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] On embedded devices, Linux is typically held in the device's firmware and may or may not be consumer-accessible.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Anaconda, one of the more popular installers, is used by Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Fedora (which uses the Fedora Media Writer) and other distributions to simplify the installation process.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Debian, Ubuntu and many others use Debian-Installer.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The process of constantly switching between distributions is often referred to as "distro hopping".
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Virtual machine software such as VirtualBox and VMware Workstation virtualize hardware allowing users to test live media on a virtual machine without installing to the real system.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Some websites like DistroWatch offer lists of distributions, and link to screenshots of operating systems as a way to get a first impression of various distributions.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Some distributions let the user install Linux on top of their current system, such as coLinux.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Linux is installed to the Windows hard disk partition, and can be started from inside Windows itself.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Virtual machines (such as VirtualBox or VMware Workstation) also make it possible for Linux to be run inside another OS.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The VM software simulates a separate computer onto which the Linux system is installed.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] After installation, the virtual machine can be booted as if it were an independent computer.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Some specific proprietary software products are not available in any form for Linux.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] As of September 2015, the Steam gaming service has over 1,500 games available on Linux, compared to 2,323 games for Mac and 6,500 Windows games.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Emulation and API-translation projects like Wine and CrossOver make it possible to run non-Linux-based software on Linux systems, either by emulating a proprietary operating system or by translating proprietary API calls (e.g., calls to Microsoft's Win32 or DirectX APIs) into native Linux API calls.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] A virtual machine can also be used to run a proprietary OS (like Microsoft Windows) on top of Linux.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Pre-built computers are usually sold with an operating system other than Linux already installed by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] This limits Linux's market share: consumers are unaware that an alternative exists, they must make a conscious effort to use a different operating system, and they must either perform the actual installation themselves, or depend on support from a friend, relative, or computer professional.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] However, it is possible to buy hardware with Linux already installed.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Lenovo, Hewlett-Packard, Dell, Affordy, Purism, Pine64 and System76 all sell general-purpose Linux laptops.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Custom-order PC manufacturers will also build Linux systems, but possibly with the Windows key on the keyboard.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Fixstars Solutions (formerly Terra Soft) sold Macintosh computers and PlayStation 3 consoles with Yellow Dog Linux installed.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] It is more common to find embedded devices sold with Linux as the default manufacturer-supported OS, including the Linksys NSLU2 NAS device, TiVo's line of personal video recorders, and Linux-based cellphones (including Android smartphones), PDAs, and portable music players.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] The current Microsoft Windows license lets the manufacturer determine the refund policy.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] With prior versions of Windows, it was possible to obtain a refund if the manufacturer failed to provide the refund by litigation in the small claims courts.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] On February 15, 1999, a group of Linux users in Orange County, California held a "Windows Refund Day" protest in an attempt to pressure Microsoft into issuing them refunds.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] There are no official figures on the popularity, adoption, downloads or installed base of Linux distributions.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] There are also no official figures for the total number of Linux systems, partly due to the difficulty of quantifying the number of PCs running Linux (see Desktop Linux adoption), since many users download Linux distributions.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Hence, the sales figures for Linux systems and commercial Linux distributions indicate a much lower number of Linux systems and level of Linux adoption than is the case; this is mainly due to Linux being free and open-source software that can be downloaded free of charge.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] A Linux Counter Project had kept track of a running guesstimate of the number of Linux systems, but did not distinguish between rolling release and standard release distributions.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] It ceased operation in August 2018, though a few related blog posts were created through October 2018.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Desktop usage statistical reports for particular Linux distributions have been collected and published since July 2014 by the Linux Hardware Project.
[src:gentoo-linux/linux-distribution] Statcounter, a web traffic analysis company, within the *operating system market share*, showed that the Linux operating systems had, according to them, 3.9% of the worldwide market share in July 2025.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] There is an ongoing effort called the Package Manager Specification project (PMS), which aims to standardise and document the behaviour of Portage, allowing the ebuild tree and Gentoo system packages to be used with alternative package managers such as Paludis and pkgcore.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Its goal is to specify the exact set of features and behaviour of package managers and ebuilds, serving as an authoritative reference for Portage.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Portage is similar to the BSD-style package management known as ports, and was originally designed with FreeBSD's ports in mind.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Portage is written in the Python programming language, and is the main utility that defines Gentoo.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Although the system itself is known as Portage, it consists of two main parts, the *ebuild* system and *emerge*.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The ebuild system takes care of the actual work of building and installing packages, while emerge provides an interface to ebuild: managing an ebuild repository, resolving dependencies and similar issues.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] A GTK-based GUI, **Porthole**, is available for working with Portage.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] There is also the **Himerge** GUI, which stands for "Haskell Interface for eMerge".
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Portage is characterized by its main function: compiling from source code the packages the user wishes to install.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] In doing so it allows customization of compiler and target-application options to fit the system's specifications and the user's own wishes.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Functionalities related to system management include: allowing parallel package-version installation, tracking cross-package dependencies, managing a database of installed packages, providing a local ebuild repository, and synchronizing of the local Portage tree with remote repositories.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Functionalities related to individual package installation include: specifying compilation settings for the target machine and choosing package components.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The **emerge** command-line tool is the heart of Portage.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The command is customizable with many options and modifiers.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The emerge tool is the most important utility for accessing the features of Portage from the command line.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The program calculates and manages dependencies, executes ebuilds and maintains the local Portage tree and database of installed packages.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The compilation settings used by ebuilds can be changed through the CFLAGS environment variable, based on the specifications of the individual computer and on the user's desire for optimization.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The emerge utility executes ebuilds in a sandbox environment.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] This way the system is protected from software executed by the ebuild and resulting binaries are only merged after a successful build and sandboxed install.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] What emerge installs as dependencies is affected by the USE flag-settings.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] They decide which optional features will be included when installing or upgrading an application.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The emerge command can also be used to download and install precompiled binary files.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The Portage system offers the use of "USE flags", which allows users to indicate which software features they would like to include (and exclude) while building packages.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] For example, there is a USE flag to include DVD support, where available, in packages compiled with the flag enabled.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The USE flags affect which dependencies are required, generally affecting which optional features will be built into a given program when it is compiled.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] For example, in packages which use a configure script, the USE flag `feature` would translate to `./configure --with-feature`.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The specification of USE flags is the usual way to configure programs on Gentoo.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] USE flags may be set manually, or via user-friendly tools such as 'ufed' (USE flag editor), which lists flags along with their description.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] A list of available USE flags is available at the Gentoo website's USE Flag Index.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Gentoo does not, by default, use binary packages as other package management systems do (like pacman or apt), employing instead a format known as the ebuild.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The official repository provides over 19,600 ebuilds, the majority of which are distributed by the Gentoo mirrors.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] New and updated ebuilds can be obtained by synchronizing the local ebuild repositories with the mirrors.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] This is done by executing the command `emaint sync -a`.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Historically, Gentoo has provided pre-compiled binary packages for many common programs, especially those which are lengthy to compile, such as Mozilla Firefox and OpenOffice.org.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] These are still installed with emerge, just by appending a "-bin" to the package name to instead install the binary version.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Gentoo does have a binary packaging format, which is a *.tbz2* file (tar with bzip2 compression) with additional metadata.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] This feature enables the building of binary packages on one system (using Portage's `buildpkg` or `quickpkg`) followed by quick installation on compatible systems (with Portage's `getbinpkg` or `emerge -K`).
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] See Portage Features in the Gentoo Linux Handbook for more information.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Portage has a set of profiles for different use cases and host targets that tend to be versioned by upstream developers, which can change how Portage functions and deals with the system when it comes to its file system hierarchy, toolchain upgrades, libc and init systems.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Profiles can also apply ebuild configurations, compiler flags, and masking in the world set.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Packages that generally just require some testing but will often work fine are said to be *keyword masked* (i.e. they are available for systems with an ACCEPT_KEYWORDS make.conf entry starting with the character `~`, such as `~x86`, `~amd64`, `~ppc`).
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] An individual *keyword masked* package can be unmasked by adding a line with the full package name and keyword to some file within the `/etc/portage/package.accept_keywords/` directory.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Users can make subdirectories here as well, allowing for custom organization.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] For example, if a masked package had multiple masked dependencies, the user could make a directory with the name of the original masked package, and put all the mask files for the package and its dependencies in that directory.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] This scheme replaces the older scheme of having `/etc/portage/package.accept_keywords` as one text file.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Packages with known problems or not considered mature enough to be candidates for stable are *hard masked* by one of the various package.mask files in /usr/portage/profiles, and such entries are generally accompanied by a comment from developers explaining the reason for the mask.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Gentoo/Alt is a project created to manage porting the portage framework and other features to other operating systems, such as Mac OS X and the free BSDs.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Gentoo/Alt was set up by Pieter Van den Abeele and Daniel Robbins after Pieter Van den Abeele founded Gentoo for Mac OS X.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Gentoo for Mac OS X was the first non-Linux project of Gentoo and focused on making the Gentoo experience available on Apple's operating system by introducing the Portage system as a separate entity.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] This was roughly similar to Fink and MacPorts, but it used Portage instead of a Debian-like or Ports-like system.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Later on, Gentoo for Mac OS X was made a subproject of Gentoo/Alt.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The project is no longer active, because its prime assumption of using and not modifying the host OS appeared not to be realistic and eventually broke most packages or made them hardly maintainable.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Gentoo for Mac OS X has been superseded by Gentoo Prefix, which is currently what Gentoo offers to Mac OS X users.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The Prefix project on Mac OS X is tested and supported on Mac OS X Tiger, Leopard and Snow Leopard on PowerPC, IA-32, and x86-64 architectures.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Gentoo/FreeBSD brings the Gentoo Linux design, structure, and tools such as Portage and the Gentoo Linux base layout to the FreeBSD operating system.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Gentoo's GNU toolchain is used instead of the original FreeBSD one.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Although the project is no longer maintained by any active Gentoo developers, there are instructions that allow installation of a full Gentoo/FreeBSD system.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] FreeBSD system ebuilds are integrated into the main portage tree, but this port is far from being complete due to the amount of packages needing to be ported and the lack of a proper Live CD (FreeSBIE's Live CD or FreeBSD setup CD is used during installation).
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The current (semi) official logo for Gentoo/FreeBSD is a daemonized "g", derived from original Gentoo Linux logo and inspired by the BSD Daemon.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] It was designed by Marius Morawski, responding to an unofficial contest launched by Diego Elio Pettenò on his blog.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Gentoo/NetBSD is a project to provide a GNU userland managed by Portage with a NetBSD kernel.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The project was started by Damian Florczyk.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Only the x86 architecture is targeted and the system as a whole is in an incomplete state.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Gentoo/OpenBSD was a Gentoo/*BSD subproject to port Gentoo features such as Portage to the OpenBSD operating system.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] It was originally started by Grant Goodyear and is deprecated.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] An install guide is provided on the project page but is also marked as deprecated.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Gentoo/DragonFlyBSD is a currently unofficial port to the DragonFlyBSD kernel.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The project is developed by Robert Sebastian Gerus.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Led by Benda Xu, "Gentoo RAP for Android Devices" installs a variant of Gentoo called Gentoo RAP in a directory prefix alongside Android.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The Linux kernel is used by both Android and Gentoo RAP.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Gentoo/Interix (eprefix) is a port of Gentoo that runs atop the Interix Subsystem for Windows which is also known as Microsoft Windows Services for UNIX (SFU) or Subsystem for Unix-based Applications (SUA).
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] A result of the Gentoo/Interix project is the ability to install and use the Portage system to emerge native Windows applications (requires Visual Studio, 2008 Express Edition will do too).
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] However, this feature does not support the wide variety of packages supported by other platforms (including Interix).
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] An unofficial port to the Solaris operating system, "Portaris", was announced around 2006, but never got into a public state.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] It was superseded by the Gentoo Prefix project.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] Started in 2011 as a Google Summer of Code project, Plan 9 For Gentoo takes the Gentoo base and overlays a userspace inspired by Plan 9.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The stated objectives of the project are to have better hardware support, better software support and to create a "culture shock" for people that have previously used Linux systems.
[src:gentoo-linux/portage-software] The project is maintained by Robert Seaton.
[src:gentoo-linux/rolling-release] A rolling release model is different from a staged or "staggered" rollout, in which an update is gradually made available to an increasing percentage of users for testing or bandwidth reasons.
[src:gentoo-linux/rolling-release] An example of a rolling release would be Arch Linux, where new packages and updates roll in constantly, and significant changes to the distribution may occur at any time by the developers.
[src:gentoo-linux/rolling-release] This is in contrast to Ubuntu Linux, which has biannual releases, with the only major changes after a release being security updates or significant bug fixes.
[src:gentoo-linux/rolling-release] Rolling release development models are one of many types of software release life cycles.
[src:gentoo-linux/rolling-release] Some modern Distributed SQL databases such as YugabyteDB also support this feature.
[src:gentoo-linux/rolling-release] A rolling release is typically implemented using small and frequent updates.
[src:gentoo-linux/rolling-release] However, simply having updates does not automatically mean that a piece of software is using a rolling release cycle; for this, the philosophy of developers must be to work with one code branch as opposed to discrete versions.
[src:gentoo-linux/rolling-release] When the rolling release is employed as the development model, software updates are typically delivered to users by a package manager on the user's personal computer, accessing through the internet a remote software repository (often via a download mirror) stored on an internet file server.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] In computing, **source code**, or simply **code** or **source**, is human readable plain text that can eventually result in controlling the behavior of a computer.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] In order to control a computer, it must be processed by a computer program – either executed directly via an interpreter or translated into a more computer-consumable form such as via a compiler.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Sometimes, code is compiled directly to machine code so that it can be run in the native language of the computer without further processing.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Many modern environments, though, involve compiling to an intermediate representation such as bytecode that can either run via an interpreter or be compiled on-demand to machine code via just-in-time compilation.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] The first programmable computers, which appeared at the end of the 1940s, were programmed in machine language (simple instructions that could be directly executed by the processor).
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Machine language was difficult to debug and was not portable between different computer systems.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Initially, hardware resources were scarce and expensive, while human resources were cheaper.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] As programs grew more complex, programmer productivity became a bottleneck.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] This led to the introduction of high-level programming languages such as Fortran in the mid-1950s.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] These languages abstracted away the details of the hardware, and were designed to express algorithms that could be understood more easily by humans.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] As instructions distinct from the underlying computer hardware, software is therefore relatively recent, dating to these early high-level programming languages such as Fortran, Lisp, and Cobol.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] The invention of high-level programming languages was simultaneous with the compilers needed to translate the source code automatically into machine code that can be directly executed on the computer hardware.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Source code is the form of code that is modified directly by humans, typically in a high-level programming language.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Object code can be directly executed by the machine and is generated automatically from the source code, often via an intermediate step, assembly language.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] While object code will only work on a specific platform, source code can be ported to a different machine and recompiled there.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] For the same source code, object code can vary significantly—not only based on the machine for which it is compiled, but also based on performance optimization from the compiler.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Most programs do not contain all the resources needed to run them and rely on external libraries.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Part of the compiler's function is to link these files in such a way that the program can be executed by the hardware.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Software developers often use configuration management to track changes to source code files (version control).
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] The configuration management system also keeps track of which object code file corresponds to which version of the source code file.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] The number of source lines of code (SLOC) is often used as a metric when evaluating the productivity of computer programmers, the economic value of a code base, effort estimation for projects in development, and the ongoing cost of software maintenance after release.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Source code is also used to communicate algorithms between parties, e.g., code snippets online or in books.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Computer programmers can find it helpful to review extant source code to learn about programming techniques.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] The sharing of source code between developers is often cited as a contributing factor to the maturing of their programming skills.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Some consider source code an expressive artistic medium.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Source code often contains comments—blocks of text marked for the compiler to ignore.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] This content is not part of the program logic, but is instead intended to help readers understand the program.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Companies often keep the source code confidential in order to hide algorithms considered a trade secret.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Proprietary, secret source code and algorithms are widely used for sensitive government applications such as criminal justice, which results in black box behavior with a lack of transparency into the algorithm's methodology.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] The result is avoidance of public scrutiny of issues such as bias.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Access to the source code (not just the object code) is essential to modifying it.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Understanding extant code is necessary to understand how it works and before modifying it.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] The rate of understanding depends both on the code base as well as the skill of the programmer.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Experienced programmers have an easier time understanding what the code does at a high level.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Software visualization is sometimes used to speed up this process.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Many software programmers use an integrated development environment (IDE) to improve their productivity.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] IDEs typically have several features built in, including a source-code editor that can alert the programmer to common errors.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Modification often includes code refactoring (improving structure without changing function) and restructuring (improving structure and function simultaneously).
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Nearly every change to code introduces new bugs or unexpected ripple effects, which require another round of fixes.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Code reviews by other developers are often used to scrutinize new code added to a project.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] The purpose of this phase is often to verify that the code meets style and maintainability standards and that it is a correct implementation of the software design.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] According to some estimates, code review dramatically reduce the number of bugs persisting after software testing is complete.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Along with software testing that works by executing the code, static program analysis uses automated tools to detect problems with the source code.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Many IDEs support code analysis tools, which might provide metrics on the clarity and maintainability of the code.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Debuggers are tools that often enable programmers to step through execution while keeping track of which source code corresponds to each change of state.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Source code files in a high-level programming language must go through a stage of preprocessing into machine code before the instructions can be carried out.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] After being compiled, the program can be saved as an object file and the loader (part of the operating system) can take this saved file and execute it as a process on the computer hardware.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Some programming languages use an interpreter instead of a compiler.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] An interpreter converts the program into machine code at run time, which makes them 10 to 100 times slower than compiled programming languages.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Source code was used this way to distribute the Unix operating system early in the history of Unix, and later to allow programs written in scripting languages (in particular the JavaScript client-side scripting language) to run on a wide variety of machines.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Software quality is an overarching term that can refer to a code's correct and efficient behavior, its reusability and portability, or the ease of modification.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] It is usually more cost-effective to build quality into a product from the start rather than try to add it later in a development process.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Higher quality code reduces lifetime cost to both suppliers and customers as via higher reliability and maintainability.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Maintainability is the quality of software enabling it to be easily modified without breaking extant functions.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Following coding conventions such as using clear function and variable names that correspond to their purpose makes maintenance easier.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Use of conditional loop statements only if the code could execute more than once, and eliminating code that will never execute can also increase understandability.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Many software development organizations neglect maintainability during the development phase, even though it will increase long-term costs.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Technical debt is incurred when programmers, often out of laziness or urgency to meet a deadline, choose quick and dirty solutions rather than build maintainability into their code.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] A common cause is underestimates in software development effort estimation, leading to insufficient resources allocated to development.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] A challenge with maintainability is that many software engineering courses do not emphasize it.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Development engineers who know that they will not be responsible for maintaining the software do not have an incentive to build in maintainability.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] The situation varies worldwide, but in the United States before 1974, software and its source code was not copyrightable and therefore always public domain software.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] In 1974, the US Commission on New Technological Uses of Copyrighted Works (CONTU) decided that "computer programs, to the extent that they embody an author's original creation, are proper subject matter of copyright".
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] Proprietary software is rarely distributed as source code.
[src:gentoo-linux/source-code] The free reusability of open-source software can speed up development.
